 Arduino Pin Types
1. Digital Input
Explanation: Reads only two states: HIGH (1) or LOW (0).
Example: Push button connected to pin 2.
IoT Use Case: Detecting door open/close in a smart security system.
2. Digital Output
Explanation: Sends HIGH or LOW signals to control devices.
Example: LED connected to pin 13.
IoT Use Case: Turning an LED or relay ON/OFF in a smart home.
3. Analog Input
Explanation: Reads analog voltage values (0–1023) using pins A0–A5.
Example: Potentiometer connected to A0.
IoT Use Case: Reading temperature or light sensor values.
4. PWM Output
Explanation: Generates Pulse Width Modulation signals on pins 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, and 11.
Example: Controlling LED brightness.
IoT Use Case: Controlling motor speed or dimming lights.
5. I2C/SPI Pins
I2C
Pins: SDA (A4), SCL (A5)
Example: OLED display or temperature sensor.
IoT Use Case: Connecting multiple sensors with only two wires.
SPI
Pins: 10 (SS), 11 (MOSI), 12 (MISO), 13 (SCK)
Example: SD card module.
IoT Use Case: Fast communication with memory cards or wireless modules.
